            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Mateo Zhao is a product of San Francisco\u2019s cultural confluence, his very name a map of his heritage. Born and raised in the foggy avenues of the Sunset District, he is the only child of a quiet, pragmatic structural engineer from Guangzhou and a vibrant second-generation Filipino-Hawaiian artist from Oahu. His home was a space of loving contrast, where communication often happened not through shared language, but through his father\u2019s meticulously crafted dishes and his mother\u2019s expressive watercolors. Kai learned early to act as an emotional translator, sensing the nuances that words failed to capture.\n\nThis upbringing organically guided him toward his calling. Feeling perpetually \"in-between\" cultural groups, he developed a profound empathy for others who felt misunderstood. After earning a B.A. at UC Santa Cruz, he returned to the city for his graduate degree at the California Institute of Integral Studies, specializing in Expressive Arts Therapy. He was drawn to the idea that healing could be found in clay, paint, and movement when words were too difficult.\n\nNow 28, Kai\u2019s professional life is a patchwork of service. He bikes his 2.8 miles from his Inner Richmond apartment to various contract jobs: two days a week at a public middle school in the Mission, helping adolescents navigate trauma, and three days at a community health clinic providing art therapy for families. His work is emotionally demanding but deeply fulfilling, allowing him to witness the small, powerful breakthroughs that art can facilitate.\n\nKai\u2019s life is grounded in simple routines. His days start with a foggy ride through Golden Gate Park and end with him and his partner, Elena, a landscape architect, experimenting with new recipes in their small kitchen. He remains deeply connected to the city of his birth, finding comfort in the familiar chill and the cultural mosaic of his neighborhood. His dream is to one day consolidate his practice and open a dedicated community arts therapy studio in the Excelsior or Bayview\u2014a welcoming, accessible space where young people, especially those from mixed-heritage backgrounds like his own, can find their voice and tell their stories without needing to say a word."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight, standing in the crossfire of silence. His father, angry, channeled his feelings into the sharp, precise chop of garlic for dinner. His mother painted the same wave over and over, a frantic turquoise slash on her canvas. Kai took a perfectly fried lumpia his father had just made and brought it to her. She took it, setting down her brush. In that small offering, he felt the tension ease. He wasn't just their son; he was their interpreter, learning that nourishment and art were two sides of the same unspoken language.\n\n2.\nIt was a bonfire at Ocean Beach, age fourteen. The other kids splintered into familiar groups\u2014the Cantonese-speaking skaters, the Tagalog-joking crew from Westmoor. He drifted between them, a ghost in a hoodie, belonging to both and neither. He watched the fire lick the fog, feeling as undefined as the space where the light met the mist. That chilly isolation wasn't a wound, but a lens. It focused his future purpose: to build a fire so welcoming that no one would ever feel left out in the cold.\n\n3.\nAt twenty, adrift in his sophomore year at Santa Cruz, words failed him. He wandered into a campus ceramics studio, the earthy smell a sudden comfort. He didn't know what he was doing, but he grabbed a lump of cold, wet clay. For an hour, he just pushed, pulled, and kneaded, his anxieties slowly transferring from his chest into his hands and into the formless shape. It was the first time he\u2019d healed himself not by thinking, but by making. He knew, with absolute clarity, what he had to do.\n\n4.\nLast year, in the Mission, a seventh-grader had been silent for weeks, her trauma a locked room. Kai gave her a stick of charcoal and paper, saying nothing. For thirty minutes, she drew a house\u2014scribbled, broken, windows like empty eyes. He felt the weight of it. Then, with a new fierceness, she drew a single, determined flower growing from a crack in its foundation. Kai\u2019s breath caught in his throat. It was proof. A story being told, a seed of resilience taking root right before his eyes.\n\n5.\nA Tuesday, a few months ago. He and Elena were trying to perfect her grandmother's pozole recipe in their tiny kitchen. Flour dusted his glasses; cilantro clung to her sleeve. He watched her sketch out a planting plan for a new client on a napkin while tasting the broth. In that moment, with the fog pressing against the windows and the scent of hominy and lime filling the air, he felt a profound ease. This partnership wasn't about translating divides, but about building something new and nourishing together, from the ground up."
